Well, that's easy for you to say.

318
00:22:48,061 --> 00:22:51,155
You have all your meals
brought to you in a pail.

319
00:22:51,264 --> 00:22:53,198
I don't get that kind of royal treatment.

320
00:22:53,299 --> 00:22:54,732
I am a trapper.

321
00:22:54,834 --> 00:22:58,634
I have to catch my food.
Which is why I make my home near you.

322
00:22:58,738 --> 00:23:02,139
- Please don't hurt me.
- Well, since you said "please."

323
00:23:04,577 --> 00:23:07,102
And just imagine how many bugs
there would be in this barn,

324
00:23:07,213 --> 00:23:09,511
no, actually, in the world,

325
00:23:09,616 --> 00:23:11,345
if spiders didn't catch them.

326
00:23:11,451 --> 00:23:13,214
Insects would take over the planet!

327
00:23:13,319 --> 00:23:15,844
The way I see it,
I'm doing everyone a favor.

328
00:23:16,156 --> 00:23:17,680
Except for the fly.

329
00:23:19,759 --> 00:23:22,387
Yes. Except for the fly.

330
00:23:25,532 --> 00:23:29,229
I think now is the time
for me to say salutations.

331
00:23:29,769 --> 00:23:30,929
What?

332
00:23:31,104 --> 00:23:32,298
Salutations.

333
00:23:33,640 --> 00:23:35,801
Okay. I'll leave.

334
00:23:35,909 --> 00:23:37,342
No, Wilbur.

335
00:23:37,944 --> 00:23:41,505
"Salutations" is just a fancy way
of saying hello.

336
00:23:41,781 --> 00:23:43,749
Oh! Hello.

337
00:23:44,951 --> 00:23:47,749
Hey, you know my name! What's yours?

338
00:23:48,254 --> 00:23:49,482
My name?

339
00:23:49,789 --> 00:23:53,088
My name is Charlotte.
Charlotte A. Cavatica.

340
00:23:53,459 --> 00:23:56,087
Charlotte. Great name!

341
00:23:56,796 --> 00:23:59,128
Thank you. I've always thought so.

342
00:23:59,232 --> 00:24:02,167
Hey, since you've said...

343
00:24:02,836 --> 00:24:04,667
You know, that word,

344
00:24:04,771 --> 00:24:06,636
does that mean we're friends?

345
00:24:08,474 --> 00:24:09,702
I suppose it does.

346
00:24:09,809 --> 00:24:11,276
Yeah!

347
00:24:14,714 --> 00:24:17,274
Golly, go see what's going-oing on
over there.

348
00:24:17,383 --> 00:24:21,410
What's going-oing...
Hey, kid, what's going on over here?

349
00:24:21,521 --> 00:24:24,752
Oh, sorry.
I just made a new friend, that's all.

350
00:24:24,991 --> 00:24:28,449
The spider. Oh, yeah. Good choice.

351
00:24:28,661 --> 00:24:30,185
Yeah, perfect.

352
00:24:31,397 --> 00:24:34,366
You picked someone
even more despised than me.

353
00:24:34,667 --> 00:24:37,192
Why would anyone despise Charlotte?

354
00:24:37,503 --> 00:24:41,200
She made that amazing web,
and she keeps bugs out of the barn.

355
00:24:41,507 --> 00:24:44,101
Look at her.
I mean, don't you think she's a little...

356
00:24:44,878 --> 00:24:46,675
What's the word?

357
00:24:49,115 --> 00:24:50,946
I think she's beautiful.

358
00:24:52,452 --> 00:24:55,250
I beg your pardon. She is hideous!

359
00:24:55,355 --> 00:24:58,290
Are we even seeing
the same ruddy creature?

360
00:24:59,058 --> 00:25:00,355
I guess not.

361
00:25:04,464 --> 00:25:05,590
Hopeless.

362
00:25:07,533 --> 00:25:10,331
What a sorry little friendship
that's going to be.

363
00:25:12,839 --> 00:25:16,468
There's an old expression that says
that ignorance is bliss,

364
00:25:16,910 --> 00:25:19,208
and I'm inclined to believe it's true,

365
00:25:19,979 --> 00:25:21,776
because, on that late spring day,

366
00:25:21,881 --> 00:25:24,247
Wilbur was as happy as a pig could be.

367
00:25:25,652 --> 00:25:28,314
And those spring days
rolled into summer days,

368
00:25:29,022 --> 00:25:31,889
days filled with endless conversation

369
00:25:31,991 --> 00:25:34,721
between the two unlikeliest of friends.

370
00:25:34,827 --> 00:25:37,125
Charlotte, what's a spring pig?

371
00:25:37,230 --> 00:25:39,130
A pig who was born in the spring.

372
00:25:39,232 --> 00:25:41,632
Oh. And I thought it meant bouncy.

373
00:25:41,734 --> 00:25:43,964
That would be a springy pig.

374
00:25:45,405 --> 00:25:48,169
"After Mrs. Mallard had laid eight eggs
in the nest,

375
00:25:48,274 --> 00:25:50,367
"she couldn't go to visit
Michael anymore,

376
00:25:50,476 --> 00:25:53,138
"because she had to sit on the eggs
to keep them warm.

377
00:25:53,246 --> 00:25:57,307
"She moved off the nest only to get
a drink of water, or to have her lunch,

378
00:25:57,417 --> 00:26:00,511
"or to count the eggs
and make sure they were all there.

379
00:26:00,820 --> 00:26:05,280
"One day, the ducklings hatched out.
First came Jack, then Kack..."

380
00:26:05,425 --> 00:26:07,120
Yeah! Yeah! This is going to be great!

381
00:26:07,226 --> 00:26:10,286
- Wilbur, what on earth are you doing?
- You'll see.

382
00:26:11,464 --> 00:26:13,432
That feels marvelous!

383
00:26:13,533 --> 00:26:16,058
Yes, over to the left a bit. Ah, yes.

384
00:26:16,169 --> 00:26:19,935
Is that a breeze I feel?
I'm 10 pounds lighter!

385
00:26:20,039 --> 00:26:21,131
- I'm next!
- I'm next!

386
00:26:21,240 --> 00:26:22,798
- I'm next!
- I'm next, too!

387
00:26:22,909 --> 00:26:25,537
- Looking pretty good, huh?
- Sure is.

388
00:26:25,845 --> 00:26:29,303
Hi, there. Are you new to the barn?
I'm Wilbur.

389
00:26:29,415 --> 00:26:31,007
Wilbur, it's me.

390
00:26:31,117 --> 00:26:32,812
Me? Great name!

391
00:26:33,019 --> 00:26:36,250
No, me. Me! Samuel! The sheep!

392
00:26:36,656 --> 00:26:39,454
Wow! What happened to you?

393
00:26:44,364 --> 00:26:47,800
The world's first pig web! Ta-da!

394
00:26:48,868 --> 00:26:51,735
I think you'd better
leave the web-spinning to me.

395
00:26:51,838 --> 00:26:53,635
After weeks and weeks,

396
00:26:53,740 --> 00:26:58,541
and I'm talking about some long weeks
of waiting and expecting,

397
00:26:58,644 --> 00:27:02,273
all the hard work has finally paid off.

398
00:27:03,449 --> 00:27:06,316
Wow! Look at them! They were eggs,

399
00:27:06,419 --> 00:27:08,546
and now they're... They're just...
Look at them!

400
00:27:08,955 --> 00:27:11,446
Wow, Gussy,
you did a really terrific job!

401
00:27:11,557 --> 00:27:13,525
They don't call me Mother Goose
for nothing.

402
00:27:13,626 --> 00:27:14,923
Congratulations.

403
00:27:15,561 --> 00:27:17,153
Would you look at that!

404
00:27:17,964 --> 00:27:20,125
Yes, thank you, thank you!

405
00:27:20,233 --> 00:27:22,133
It wasrt easy, but I managed.

406
00:27:22,235 --> 00:27:23,702
You managed?

407
00:27:24,237 --> 00:27:26,569
I'm kidding, honey. We managed.

408
00:27:27,573 --> 00:27:30,872
Six, seven. Werert there eight eggs?

409
00:27:31,144 --> 00:27:33,840
Could this be a dud?

410
00:27:33,946 --> 00:27:35,777
Golly! Golly!

411
00:27:35,882 --> 00:27:37,281
- Golly!
- Whoa!

412
00:27:37,383 --> 00:27:40,910
Whoa, there, Father Goose!
I'm just trying to help the happy couple.

413
00:27:41,020 --> 00:27:43,113
What do you want
with a rotten egg, anyway?

414
00:27:43,222 --> 00:27:45,986
I want a rotten egg

415
00:27:46,092 --> 00:27:49,186
for the simple reason that...
You never know.

416
00:27:49,295 --> 00:27:50,853
This one didn't make it.

417
00:27:50,963 --> 00:27:52,828
I think we have to let it go.

418
00:27:54,367 --> 00:27:55,834
Oh, take it!

419
00:27:55,935 --> 00:27:59,029
And add it
to that nasty-asty collection of yours.

420
00:28:00,039 --> 00:28:01,870
Last one out is a rotten egg!

421
00:28:04,243 --> 00:28:05,904
- Well, I thought it was funny.
- I should have pecked him!

422
00:28:06,012 --> 00:28:07,570
Don't you break that egg, rat.

423
00:28:07,680 --> 00:28:10,342
A broken rotten egg would make
this barn stink to high heaven.

424
00:28:10,450 --> 00:28:12,315
That would be a change.

425
00:28:12,785 --> 00:28:15,652
Why are you laughing, Bits?
He just said we stink.

426
00:28:15,755 --> 00:28:18,451
Oh, yeah. This is good.
This will come in handy.

427
00:28:23,162 --> 00:28:25,790
You really are a handsome devil.

428
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:29,331
Oh, boy.

429
00:28:50,490 --> 00:28:52,219
Egg-xactly!

430
00:29:01,601 --> 00:29:04,365
Saw a big old spider in the doorway!
Gonna go catch it!

431
00:29:04,470 --> 00:29:06,404
No, Avery! Come back here!

432
00:29:06,506 --> 00:29:08,872
- Here, spidey-spidey.
- You can't do that!

433
00:29:10,877 --> 00:29:11,969
Stop!

434
00:29:15,615 --> 00:29:17,549
- Gotcha!
- No, no, Avery!

435
00:29:18,451 --> 00:29:21,284
Wilbur, no! Come on, Wilbur, get off!

436
00:29:22,121 --> 00:29:24,419
Wilbur, Wilbur, why did you do that?

437
00:29:25,758 --> 00:29:28,283
Avery! No!

438
00:29:38,070 --> 00:29:39,901
That stinks!

439
00:29:40,006 --> 00:29:41,974
Oh, that is gross.

440
00:29:47,446 --> 00:29:48,811
Man, is that you?

441
00:29:48,915 --> 00:29:51,907
No. I smell a smell, though.
Think it's scary guy?

442
00:29:52,018 --> 00:29:54,714
- He's trying to stink us away from the...
- Corn!

443
00:29:59,358 --> 00:30:01,690
Guess the yolk's on me.

444
00:30:02,962 --> 00:30:04,623
That is one ripe egg.

445
00:30:07,934 --> 00:30:10,232
That stinks good!

446
00:30:10,536 --> 00:30:12,128
That is disgusting!

447
00:30:13,506 --> 00:30:17,374
- We told you not to break that egg.
- Now look what you've done, rat!

448
00:30:17,476 --> 00:30:19,239
It saved Charlotte, didn't it?

449
00:30:19,345 --> 00:30:22,837
Yeah, ingrates.
I saved the leggy lady's life.

450
00:30:23,416 --> 00:30:26,010
- You mean that as a good thing, right?
- Of course.

451
00:30:26,118 --> 00:30:28,018
I do have a few eyes, you know,

452
00:30:28,120 --> 00:30:30,247
and I think
Wilbur did most of the saving.

453
00:30:30,356 --> 00:30:32,381
I know. Ironic, isn't it?

454
00:30:32,491 --> 00:30:36,587
He's saving you,
and they're saving him for Christmas.

455
00:30:36,696 --> 00:30:37,754
Templeton!

456
00:30:37,863 --> 00:30:39,194
What's Christmas?

457
00:30:40,800 --> 00:30:42,859
The day you'll be cured.

458
00:30:43,135 --> 00:30:44,534
But I'm not sick.

459
00:30:45,204 --> 00:30:46,831
I didn't say you were sick.

460
00:30:46,939 --> 00:30:50,102
- Uh-oh. That was a mistake.
- Yep. Typical rat.

461
00:30:50,209 --> 00:30:54,236
What? You're going to lie
to the future football here? Okay.

462
00:30:54,780 --> 00:30:58,580
But it's a sad statement when
I'm the most honest guy in the place.

463
00:30:58,751 --> 00:31:01,015
Templeton, what are you talking about?

464
00:31:01,220 --> 00:31:03,484
Come winter,
the farmer will be checking you

465
00:31:03,589 --> 00:31:05,819
into the old smokehouse hotel.

